did.unittitle: Mick Moloney Irish-American Music and Popular Culture Collection, Part III: Papers
did.abstract:
The Mick Moloney Collection of Irish-American Music and Popular Culture is the largest collection in the Archives of Irish America at New York University and constitutes an aurally and visually rich resource for scholars and students of the Irish-American experience.
Part III of the Mick Moloney Irish-American Music and Popular Culture Collection consists of Dr. Moloney's papers, acquired in the course of his career as folklorist, producer, musician and academic. The papers include research, administrative and personal files; items related to song and music collecting; concert posters, programs and memorabilia; and photographs related to all aspects of Moloney's professional life.
NOTE: This collection is stored offsite and advance notice is required for use.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Material at the Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives
relatedmaterial.p: The Mick Moloney Irish American Music and Popular Culture Collection is composed of five parts. Taken together, they illustrate Dr. Moloney's career long engagement with Irish-American culture across a wide variety of media with a particular focus on Irish and Irish-American music.
Mick Moloney Irish American Music and Popular Culture Collection, Part I: Commercial Recordings (AIA 031.1)
Mick Moloney Irish American Music and Popular Culture Collection, Part II: Field Recordings (AIA 031.2)
Mick Moloney Irish American Music and Popular Culture Collection, Part IV: Irish Americana (AIA 031.4)
Mick Moloney Irish American Music and Popular Culture Collection, Part V: Videotapes (AIA 031.5)
Dorothy Hayden Cudahy Irish Memories Collection (AIA 001) Susan McKeown Papers (AIA 032)

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p:
The papers are arranged in six series:
Series I: General, 1806-2011
Series II: Individuals, 1879-2010
Series III: Academic, 1889-2011
Series IV: Song and Music Collecting, 1867-2000
Series V: Concert Memorabilia, 1971-2011
Series VI: Photos, ca.1930-2002
The photos are further subdivided into slides, prints, negatives and film.
The series are arranged alphabetically except for Concert Memorabilia, which is arranged chronologically.

The original order of series I-IV was maintained except in the case of obvious misfiling; Dr. Moloney employed various people to organize his papers prior to accession with sometimes unpredictable results.

bioghist.head: Historical/Biographical Note
bioghist.p: Dr. Mick Moloney (b. 1944 Limerick, Ireland) is Global Distinguished Professor of Music and Irish Studies at New York University (NYU). He immigrated to the United States in 1973 and was based in Philadelphia until moving to New York City in 2006. A musician and folklorist, he has recorded and produced over forty albums of traditional music and acted as advisor for scores of festivals and concerts, as well as being artistic director for the musical ensemble The Green Fields of America. In 1999 Mick Moloney was awarded the National Heritage Award from the National Endowment for the Arts, the highest official honor a traditional artist can receive in the United States. He is the author of the book and CD Far from the Shamrock Shore (2002), as well as numerous essays on Irish music and musical culture, co-editor of Close to the Floor: Irish Dance from the Boreen to Broadway (2009) and has a Ph.D. in folklore and folklife from the University of Pennsylvania.
Nov 15, 1944 - Born, "Glanleam," Castletroy, Limerick
1968 -1971 Member of The Johnstons
1973 - Matriculates at U Penn as a Doctoral Candidate in Folklore
1975 - Co-founds the Philadelphia Ceili Group Festival
1976 - Curates Irish music component of the Smithsonian Folklife Festival

1976 - Receives NEA grant to record Irish music in NY, Boston, Chicago, Philadelphia and Cleveland
1977 - Founds Folklife Center at International House
1978 - Founds Green Fields of America, first federally funded touring group of traditional musicians
1978/1979 - Maintains private booking agency
1978 - Produces Across the Western Ocean radio series with NEA funds
1980 - Fieldwork for the American Folklife Center at the Library of Congress culminating in the curation of the Folklife component of the 1982 World's Fair
1981 - Freelance writer for Radio Telefis Eireann (RTE)
1981 - Writes and produces the film, Did Your Mother Come From Ireland?
1982 - Begins 12-year association with Villanova University as Adjunct Professor in the English Department and Honors Program
1982 - Founds Irish Week at the Augusta Heritage Center, Elkins College, WV
1983 - Tours Africa with the federally funded Festival of Traditional American Dance
1985 - Tours Central America with the federally funded Festival of Mountain Music and Dance
1987 - Directs the International Village Fair for International House, Philadelphia, PA
1990 - Produces the Concert for Joe Doherty, Symphony Space, New York, NY
1992 - Receives Doctorate in Folklore from the University of Pennsylvania
1992 - Begins Folklife Tours of Ireland and Scotland
1996 - Produces the Concert for Peace, Symphony Space, New York, NY
1999 - Receives National Heritage Fellowship Award from the National Endowment of the Arts.
1999 - Joins NYU as Adjunct Professor
2006 - Appointed Global Distinguished Professor of Music and Irish Studies at NYU
For further biographical information, see:
Steve Winnick, “From Limerick Rake to Solid Man: The Musical Life of Mick Moloney,” Dirty Linen, No. 48 (October/November 1993)

custodhist.head: Provenance
custodhist.p: New York University’s Division of Libraries, in conjunction with Glucksman Ireland House at New York University, purchased the Mick Moloney Collection for the Archives of Irish America in 2006. Until the Collection was transferred to New York University, under the supervision of Dr. Michael Nash, Head of the Tamiment Library, the materials were stored in Dr. Moloney’s house in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: The Mick Moloney Irish American Music and Popular Culture Collection is composed of five parts. Taken together, they illustrate Dr. Moloney's career long engagement with two centuries of Irish-American musical culture (1806 to 2011, bulk dates 1975-2000) across a wide variety of media and from at least three perspectives: academic, professional and performative. Part III of this collection consists of Dr. Moloney's papers. It features research, administrative and personal files; items related to song and music collecting; concert posters, programs and memorabilia; and photographs. These primary and secondary source materials flesh out the voices, performances and stories embodied in the commercial and field recordings found in Parts I and II of the Moloney Collection, while documenting the shape and contour of Moloney's own career.

Part III provides resources for scholars whose focus is the Irish-American experience. Broad themes of immigration and assimilation can be viewed through the lens of Irish-America's engagement with and expression of its own popular culture, primarily its music. The era most well documented in the Moloney collection (1975-2000) witnessed both a reinvestment by Irish-America in its cultural traditions, and a transition of its musical traditions from home to the stage accompanied by unprecedented national recognition. In this regard, Part III may be of interest to those interested in tracing shifts in federal policies regarding arts funding and programming as well as those interested in the valorization of ethnicity in the U.S. from the 1970s on. In addition, one of Moloney's interests during this period was the rise in prominence of female performers of traditional music, of potential interest to those whose focus is gender.

Researchers of the 19th century will find much of interest in Part III relating to the Irish presence on and repertoire of the New York stage, while those interested in 20th century Irish performers will find rare photographs, interesting song and music collections and inforamtive subject files from 1930s on. Early Irish performers in Philadelphia are particularly well represented.

And finally, Part III also offers students of folklore and ethnicity a wide sampling of scholarly literature; academic articles and student papers provide a double perspective on the field and its evolution from the 1970s through the 1990s.

Series I: General, 1806-2011 consists of subject files pertaining primarily to Moloney's professional life as a performer, promoter, producer and fieldworker, supplemented by items of personal interest. An extensive collection (labeled "Bookings") of contracts and correspondence minutely detail Moloney's performance engagements from 1977-2005, while "Recording Projects" files document the behind-the-scenes studio work for many albums that have become classics. Financial records and ephemera pertaining to major labels, Green Linnet, Shanachie, Topic and Transatlantic provide an interesting glimpse into the marketing and business models applied to Irish music from the 1970s forward. Of particular interest are a complete run of the fledgling Shanachie label's quirky newsletters from the 1970s, and a collection of record catalogs dating back to the 1920s.

A large percentage of the General files pertain to Moloney's involvement in various federally funded projects beginning with his work organizing the Irish music section of the 1976 Smithsonian Institution Festival of American Folklife, followed by his work documenting the Irish community in conjunction with the Chicago Ethnic Arts Project in 1977. The founding and touring details of his federally-funded ensemble, the Green Fields of America, are evidenced. Materials relating to an NEA project documenting the folklife around Knoxville, TN, which culminated in his work curating the folklife component of the 1982 World's Fair held in that city are also present.

Moloney devoted a full year organizing the International Village Fair sponsored by Philadelphia's International House in 1987. The voluminous records detailing all aspects of this festival compliment the extensive photo and slide documentation found elsewhere in Part III of the Moloney collection. In addition, his involvement with the founding and early days of the Philadelphia Ceili Group Festival is well-documented as is the Irish Week at the Augusta Heritage Center in Elkins, WV, which Moloney founded in 1982.

The General series also contains a great deal of documentation pertaining to two large broadcast projects concerning immigration and the Irish-American experience. Grant proposals, edited drafts of scripts, glossy fundraising packages and budgets witness the careful development for two proposed multi-part series for Radio Telefis Eireann entitled The Green Fields of America and Emigrants and Exiles. The series were never produced.

Significant among the materials collected by Moloney through personal interest are items pertaining to all aspects of Irish music, with a particular focus on the Irish-American experience. Several decades worth of newsletters issued by various Irish-American "Celtic" Societies, and some obscure journals offer insight into the engagement of grass-roots organizations and academics with Irish and Irish-American identity. Of additional interest is a large amount of photocopied material from turn-of-the-century newspapers, the Gaelic-American and the New York Clipper.

A great volume of Moloney's business and personal correspondence is also included in this series, and it should be noted that it is sometimes difficult to draw a clear distinguish between the two categories. Correspondence related to Moloney's academic career is found in the Academic series.

Series II: Individuals, 1879-2010 consists of files collected by Moloney about individuals and groups through his personal and research interests and/or in the course of his professional and academic life. The majority of the individuals and groups are Irish or Irish-American, are closely associated with Irish traditional music, and in many cases are performers. The remainder are primarily Irish and Irish-American academics, poets and writers such as the Philadelphia historian Dennis Clark.
Of particular note are the items related to Moloney himself; articles, reviews, press packets and yearly planners provide an intimate glimpse of Moloney's private and public lives.

A "mini-collection" of vintage items given to Moloney by fiddler and radio host Tommy Caulfield forms an interesting component of Series II. Ledger books, correspondence, radio receipts and advertisements, and concert programs paint a picture of the Irish Musicians' Association and the Irish Musicians' Union current in Philadelphia from at least the 1940s.

Series III: Academic, 1889-2011 consists primarily of research and course materials accrued by Moloney during his teaching assignments at Villanova, NYU, Georgetown and Boston College, as well as in the course of acquiring his PhD from the University of Pennsylvania. These materials include syllabi, reading lists, correspondence, handwritten research notes and the text and notes of fourteen Moloney lectures. A wide body of research materials on the topics of folklore and ethnicity are represented both in photocopied academic articles and by student papers.

Series IV: Song and Music Collecting, 1867-2000 contains lyrics, tunes and songs, both published and in manuscript form, collected by Moloney for performance and personal use. Of the songbooks (which contain lyrics and musical notation), John Ward's Private Collection of Irish Comic Songs is of particular note, while the twenty photocopied songsters (containing lyrics alone) compliment those found in Part IV of the Moloney collection. There are also manuscripts of dance tunes, including some Moloney compositions.

Series V: Concert Memorabilia, 1971-2011 consists of programs, fliers, brochures and ephemera related to forty years of Moloney's performance career. This series provides a visual compliment to many of the concert performances found in Part II of the Moloney collection. It includes many oversized items including early Johnstons posters and one in Spanish promoting the 1985 Festival of Mountain Music and Dance Central American tour.

Series VI: Photos, c.1930-2002 provides a visual reference for all parts of the Moloney collection. Performers, events and venues which appear in the rest of the papers and on the field recordings are nearly all represented here across three formats: slides, prints and negatives. Some subjects with particularly extensive coverage are: Moloney's performing partnerships with Eugene O'Donnell, Robbie O'Connell and Jimmy Keane; at least a decade of Moloney's package tours of Ireland and Scotland ; the 1987 International Village Fair hosted by Philadelphia's International House; ethnic performance programming at International House; step dance competitions and classes (some featuring Jean and Cara Butler); and slides prepared to accompany Moloney's lectures.
Of particular note is an abundance of contact sheets, often with corresponding negatives, that document informal gatherings of musicians with whom Moloney played and performed regularly.
Series VI also contains a 35mm. print of Moloney's 1981 film focusing on the Mulvihill School of Irish Music in the Bronx entitled, Did Your Mother Come From Ireland?
